body:
The following RTL generates a 'Signal unoptimizable: Feedback to clock or circular logic' warning despite the presence of split_var:

```systemverilog
module test (
  output any_err_o,

  input loop_err,
  input imem_addr_err
);
  typedef struct packed {
    logic loop;
    logic bad_insn_addr;
  } err_bits_t;

  err_bits_t err_bits /*verilator split_var*/;

  logic non_insn_addr_software_err;

  assign err_bits.loop          = loop_err;
  assign err_bits.bad_insn_addr = imem_addr_err & ~non_insn_addr_software_err;

  assign non_insn_addr_software_err = err_bits.loop;

  assign any_err_o = |err_bits;
endmodule
```

If you ditch the intermediate `non_insn_addr_software_err` the warning goes away:

```systemverilog
module test (
  output any_err_o,

  input loop_err,
  input imem_addr_err
);
  typedef struct packed {
    logic loop;
    logic bad_insn_addr;
  } err_bits_t;

  err_bits_t err_bits /*verilator split_var*/;

  assign err_bits.loop          = loop_err;
  assign err_bits.bad_insn_addr = imem_addr_err & ~err_bits.loop;

  assign any_err_o = |err_bits;
endmodule
```

It also goes away if you ditch the struct and use separate signals instead:

```systemverilog
module test (
  output any_err_o,

  input loop_err,
  input imem_addr_err
);
  logic err_bits_loop;
  logic err_bits_bad_insn_addr;

  logic non_insn_addr_software_err;

  assign err_bits_loop          = loop_err;
  assign err_bits_bad_insn_addr = imem_addr_err & ~non_insn_addr_software_err;

  assign non_insn_addr_software_err = err_bits_loop;

  assign any_err_o = err_bits_loop | err_bits_bad_insn_addr;
endmodule
```
I believe the three pieces of RTL are functionally equivalent and did think split_var effectively turns the first example into the third, though clearly isn't in this case.

Tested with latest master as of time of posting (Verilator 4.215 devel rev v4.214-2-g0ef9087f), also seen in v4.210

This is a cut-down version of the actual RTL I'm working with where the `non_insn_addr_software_err` signal has more stuff factored into it so the second example isn't a great workaround.

Full output when built with `verilator -cc --report-unoptflat verilator_test.sv` is:

```
%Warning-UNOPTFLAT: verilator_test.sv:32:9: Signal unoptimizable: Feedback to clock or circular logic: 'test.non_insn_addr_software_err'
   32 |   logic non_insn_addr_software_err;
      |         ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
                    ... For warning description see https://verilator.org/warn/UNOPTFLAT?v=4.215
                    ... Use "/* verilator lint_off UNOPTFLAT */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
                    verilator_test.sv:32:9:      Example path: test.non_insn_addr_software_err
                    verilator_test.sv:34:33:      Example path: ASSIGNW
                    verilator_test.sv:30:14:      Example path: test.err_bits
                    verilator_test.sv:37:37:      Example path: ASSIGNW
                    verilator_test.sv:32:9:      Example path: test.non_insn_addr_software_err
                    ... Widest candidate vars to split:
                        verilator_test.sv:30:14:  test.err_bits, width 2, fanout 14, can split_var
                    ... Most fanned out candidate vars to split:
                        verilator_test.sv:30:14:  test.err_bits, width 2, fanout 14, can split_var
                    ... Suggest add /*verilator split_var*/ to appropriate variables above.
dot -Tpdf -o ~/a.pdf obj_dir/Vverilator_test_055_unoptflat.dot
%Error: Exiting due to 1 warning(s)
```

Note the split_var suggestion is suggesting err_bits gets a split_var which it already has.
